      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><div class="seriesmeta">This entry is part 22 of 23 in the series <a href="http://www.michellemacphearson.com/series/31-day-internet-marketing-makeover/" title="series-721">31 Day Internet Marketing Makeover</a></div><br /><p>Welcome to Day 22 of the Internet Marketing Makeover (#31DIMM for short)!</p>
<p>We all surround ourselves by what we are comfortable with, and online, that might mean the blogs we regularly read, the <a href="http://twitter.com/michellem"  class="alinks_links" title="Michelle MacPhearson on Twitter"  rel="external">Twitter</a> friends and the Facebook fans we interact with.</p>
<p>But now that we&#8217;ve established a lead generation funnel for our sites, it&#8217;s time to break out of that comfort zone and bring new prospects, customers and friends into our sphere of influence.</p>
<h3>DAY 22 OBJECTIVE</h3>
<p>Begin guest posting at other popular industry blogs.</p>
<h3>DAY 22 ASSIGNMENT</h3>
<p>Most likely, you know who the &#8220;big player&#8221; bloggers are in your niche.</p>
<p>Make a list of the top 10.</p>
<p>If you don&#8217;t know who&#8217;s blogging in your niche, it&#8217;s high time to find out! Use Google Blog Search and Technorati to get started, from those popular blogs you&#8217;ll often find links to other popular blogs in your niche.  List &#8216;em!</p>
<p><a title="Guest spot" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/47477979@N00/2707705079/" target="_blank"><img class="alignright" src="http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3112/2707705079_858aa47c98_m.jpg" border="0" alt="Guest spot" /></a>Check those 10 most popular blogs in your niche and see if they have a page on their site with information about guest posting.  Some will not, in this case you&#8217;ll need to use a contact form or social media profile to get in touch with the blogger and see if they&#8217;re open to your authoring a guest post.</p>
<p>There are many nuances involved in securing a guest post slot, particularly with the most popular blogs within a niche (they&#8217;re sometime inundated).  You don&#8217;t want to be too pushy, but assertive and confident is necessary.  You want to get a link back to your site as part of the guest post, otherwise it&#8217;s just your name, and few readers will bother to look you up and find your site.</p>
<p>You&#8217;ll find Chris Garrett&#8217;s &#8220;<a title="Chris Garrett - Guest Posting" href="http://www.michellemacphearson.com/guestposting/">Guest Posting For Quality Links and Targeted Traffic</a>&#8221; a thorough look at every aspect of guest posting, including the delicate negotiation process. (Chris authored the ProBlogger print title with Darren Rowse, among his many other accolades).</p>
<p>When you do write your guest post, make it the best work you can muster &#8211; this is your time to shine!  You want to &#8220;Wow&#8221; the readers so much they can&#8217;t help but click through to your site from your &#8220;About the Author&#8221; line and subscribe.  (Chris discusses several methods on can use to drive traffic back to your own site in his <a href="http://www.michellemacphearson.com/guestposting/">Guest Posting book</a> as well).</p>
<p>This isn&#8217;t the time to waffle and be a wallflower &#8211; have strong opinions and support them proudly.  Try to cover something different that what everyone else is writing about, or at least put a new spin on a familiar topic.</p>
<p>Having written for the top 10 blogs in your industry, you&#8217;ll soon be seen as a leader in your niche also.  Don&#8217;t abandon your newfound subscribers, continue to provide them with great content and when you do recommend a product or service, they will listen!</p>
